Improvements in connection with Dolls' Eyes.
column13: 111,745. Bell, W. Jan 9, 1917. Dolls. - Relates to mechanism for moving dolls' eyes laterally under the action of a pendulous weight. The eyeballs C can turn freely in sockets B at the sides 1 of a wire gallery A, which is hinged at G<1> to a wire cradle G fixed inside the doll's head below the eyes, so that the gallery can move up and down vertically. A wire spring H holds the gallery in place, and. the rear ends of rods F fixed to the eyeballs are connected by a cross-bar D on which the weight E acts. The weight is suspended from the upper part of the inside of the doll's head by a string E<3> attached to a wire E<1> which passes through an eye E<2> in the bar D. On tilting the doll to the left or right, the weight falls over and the eyeballs turn together in the direction opposite to that in which the weight moves.

21,515. Bell, W. Oct. 7. Latches; locks, key.-Relates to latches operated from the outside of the door by a key and, according to the Provisional Specification, applied to closet and coal-cellar doors &c. A latch C, Fig. 4, is pivoted between two projections and on the inner door-plate B, and is retained by a doublebevelled catch E secured to the side frame. A guard H and a stop J for the key end may be secured to the plate B. The key D, when turned, presses a projection on the latch C and lifts it. Fig. 6 shows the latch C used for a left-hand door; for a right-hand door, it is bent the other way. The catch is reversible.

column13: 12,140. Bell, W. May 28. Knobs and handles, attaching; fastenings.-Re- lates to the attachment of knobs, handles, and like fittings to the spindles of locks and latches, furniture, &c. The knob or fitting A is bored to receive a square spindle C. The base B of the knob is formed with guides to receive a spring- controlled sliding bolt or catch D, which is slotted to encircle the spindle. The movement of the catch is limited by a stop such as the shoulder H. The end of the spindle is bevelled so that it may be forced past the catch, which engages a notch in the spindle and so locks it in position. The catch is forced out of engagement with the spindle by pushing back a finger E, which projects through the base of the fitting. The base is closed by a cover-plate. In another arrangement, the guides for the catch are formed in the cover-plate, which is secured in a recess in the base. The spindle is circular, and the notch for receiving the catch extends entirely around the spindle.

column13: 27,529. Bell, W., and Bell, H. B. Dec. 3. Underlays and make-ready arrangements.-Halftone printing-blocks are constructed in such a manner that overlays or make-ready appliances are rendered practically unnecessary. In one method the face and back of the plate have the print burnt in, that on the back being a reverse of that on the face. The back is deeply etched and the plate is subjected to pressure beneath a sheet of lead, leather, gutta-percha, &c. The plate is pressed either when hot or cold. The face of the plate is thus rendered partly in relief and it is then etched ready for printing. By another method, a second plate is deeply etched and coated with an adhesive mixture consisting of Stockholm tar, resin, and gutta-percha. The half-tone plate, with the print burnt in, is then placed face upwards upon the etched plate and subjected to pressure as before. The two plates adhere together and the upper face is then etched. A sheet of bichromated gelatin which has been printed and developed may be used instead of the etched metal plate.

Sterilisation system and method of use thereof
column13: A system for sterilisation or disinfection via ozone generation means comprising an ozone generation cell 14, fan 16 and timer 20, and at least one manifold (22, fig. 2). The timer 20 controls the cell 14 power, enabling user selectable ozone generation or use periods, of which there may be a plurality. The cell 14 may be dormant when not in use, and there may be a motion detector. The system may include a power supply, converting incoming power into direct current (DC). There may be a high voltage generator, which may be a pulsed width modulation (PWM) controlled switch 8 and a high frequency high voltage transformer 10, with the output applied to the cell 14, which may be linear and glass. The fan 16, of which there may be a plurality, can cool the cell and direct ozone. Ozone may be directed by diffusers and tubing attached to the manifold (22, fig. 2). A microprocessor 18 may control the fan 16 and timer 20. The system may be used in retail, in a device, of which there is a method disclosed.

Improvements in Driving Gear for Bicycles and other Road Vehicles.
column13: 20,717. Bell, W., and Bell, J. T. Sept. 10. Conveying rotary motion. - A driving-gear for bicycles and other road vehicles is characterized by a pair of reciprocating nuts d in engagement with right- and left-hand screw-threads c, c' upon the driven shaft a. A sleeve h secured to the crank axle k is slotted at g to engage rollers f upon a non-rotatable drum e, the nuts d being provided with external ratchet-teeth for engagement with pawls carried by the ends of the drum. To prevent rotation of the drum and yet to allow its axial motion with the nuts, the drum is grooved to engage stays secured to the fixed cover n and to a freely-mounted disk p. Means such as a ring or washer applied to each end of the drum retain the nuts within it. The hollow screw-threaded shaft a is secured to the driving-wheel b to which an increased rate of rotation is imparted. The screwthreads need not be arranged to cross each other but may be separate.

column12: Improvements in or connected with Electrolytic Cells.
column13: 25,890. Bell, G., and Bell, G. W. Nov. 8. Chlorine; hydrogen.- Relates to apparatus for the electrolysis of solutions, especially of alkaline chlorides to obtain alkali and chlorine, by the use of a moving mercury cathode. In the example shown, there are three tiers of compartments, the two outer sets a containing (1) h o r izontal carbon anodes i passing through stuffing- boxes i<1>, (2) the electrolyte, and (3) a mercury cathode layer on the slightly - inclined floors. Outlets f<1> for gas, arranged above the level of the electrolyte, and serving also as overflow pipes for the electrolyte, lead to two mains f, each provided with a valve g. The valves being shut, the pressure accumulates in the chamber a, as chlorine is developed during electrolysis, and the mercury amalgam formed is forced thereby below an amalgamated bar j, forming a lute and connected to conductors leading to the dynamo &c. The amalgam then passes through glass tubes e having U-tubes or like gauges thereon, to the central tier of a chamber b containing water, which decomposes the amalgam, reforming the mercury and combining with the sodium to form caustic-soda solution. The water, in the example shown, enters the top chamber at l, and overflows successively through tubes l<1> to the other chambers, finally leaving the lowest chamber as a strong solution. Hydrogen is evolved during this reaction, and escapes through branch tubes m<1> to the main m. The valve of one tube f is then operated by any mechanism and the chlorine allowed to escape. The pressure immediately falls in that chamber a, and the mercury flows back. Or the mercury may be driven back by allowing the hydrogen to accumulate in the vessels b. The electrolytic action then re-commences. By setting the two valves g accordingly, the two tiers of chambers a may be worked alternately. In the example shown, the valve g is closed or opened at fixed intervals by a double hydraulic tumbling basin h charged with water from a supply tap h<1>. Other methods of operating the valve may be used, either electrical or mechanical. Strong brine is supplied to the chambers a, the supply being regulated by a valve also actuated by the tumbling basin h, and opened when the corresponding valve g is opened.

column12: Improvements in or connected with Electrolytic Cells or Apparatus.
column13: 10,655. Bell, G., and Bell, G. W. May 23. Chlorine; hydrogen.- In an apparatus for electrolysing alkaline chlorides, a liquid metal electrode is caused to move from an eleotrolytic cell a to adjacent chambers b by periodically varying the gas pressure in these chambers. The apparatus may consist of slate slabs h, h<1> and an iron wall g, the electrolytic compartment a being separated by iron and slate partitions d, which nearly touch the lower slab A'. Several cells may be arranged vertically. A mercury cathode is carried on a raised part of the lower slab h<1>, a thin layer of the mercury being always retained by ribs c on the raised part. Connection is made with it by a bolt o. An anode with radial arms i is supported over the cathode. The electrolytic solution is supplied at one end of the cell a, and is discharged, with the chlorine evolved, through an opening f<1> into a vertical pipe. The side chambers b are supplied with water through bent pipes, and the caustic solution from them overflows into a vertical pipe, having a liquid seat at its lower end. The hydrogen produced in the side chambers is discharged through a pipe m and a valve, which is periodically closed to cause the mercury to enter the electrolytic cell, and opened to allow it to return, by automatic electromagnetic apparatus shown in Fig. 3. The valve is opened directly by an electromagnet q, when the circuit of this is closed by mercury in a vessel r touching a contact wire r'. The contact compartment of the vessel r is connected by a cock r<5> to another compartment, in which the gas pressure in the hydrogen pipe m acts on the mercury, to close the circuit. When the valve is opened, a switch t', connected with it, independently closes the circuit of the electromagnet q, through a lower contact r<2> in the vessel r ; the valve is thus held open until the mercury falls below the lower contact r<2>. The cock r<5> regulates the rate of fall. Glycerine is placed on the mercury in the contact compartment to prevent sparking. In a modification, the valve is arranged to connect the hydrogen pipe alternately to a reservoir and to a pump from which hydrogen is supplied under pressure. Otherwise the mercury may be moved by pressure of a head of liquid.

METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR TESTING EARTH FORMATIONS COMPOSED OF PARTICLES OF VARIOUS SIZES
column13: In the representative embodiments of the new and improved methods and apparatus disclosed herein for testing earth formations of differing compositions, fluid-admitting means carrying a selectively-sized filter of a unique design are selectively extended into sealing engagement with a potentially-producible earth formation and operated so as to establish communication with the isolated formation without the fluid-admitting means being plugged with mudcake from the formation wall. Should, however, loose formation materials enter the fluid-admitting means as the testing is conducted, the filter is uniquely arranged to collect these loose materials and halt the further erosion of such materials from the formation wall so as to assure continued communication with the isolated formation.

A shaped charge tubing cutter includes a minimal contact suspension to isolate the cutter explosive from the housing and sub structure. A charge detonation booster main-cavity is located on the juncture of the charge truncation planes. Explosive in the booster main-cavity is detonated by a shielded primer path. Explosive density in the primer path is less than the main-cavity density. A dense, powdered metal SC liner and an abruptly stepped jet window in the tubing cutter housing improve performance. The axial span of the jet window is preferably aligned with the axial span between the liner bases. A testing apparatus and procedure inexpensively verifies downhole performance.

The gate latch comprises at least two housings wherein the first housing is mountable to a stationary object such as an existing fence or structure and the second housing is mountable to a moveable object such as a gate. column13: A ladder rack to carry a ladder on a pick-up truck having a front and rear rack mounting openings in a top portion of the side wall of the bed box, comprising: a front and a rear ladder support each having, i) an upright insertion portion sized to be closely received within one of the mounting openings in the pick-up truck; ii) a lateral offset portion carried by, and extending inwardly from a top portion of the upright insertion portion; iii) a mast portion carried by an inner end portion of the lateral offset portion; iv) a lateral ladder carrying portion extending laterally from an upper portion of the mast; v) longitudinal movement prevention means to prevent longitudinal movement of the ladder when it is supported on the lateral carrying portions; and, vi) a swinging arm extending from above to below the ladder to limit lateral ladder movement, when a central portion of the swinging arm is maintained in an upright position adjacent to the ladder. In use after the front and rear brackets are inserted within the rack openings, opposite ends of the ladder may be slid over the lateral ladder carrying portions of the supports thereby supporting the ladder parallel to the side wall of the bed; and finally, the swinging arm may be swung to an engaged position to thereby limit lateral movement of the ladder on the lateral carrying portion.

column12: Antivibration device for automobiles and like vehicles

column13: 1,219,122. Automatic frequency control; light modulators. VARIAN ASSOCIATES. 12 Jan., 1968 [19 Jan., 1967], No. 1845/68. Headings H3A and H4F. [Also in Division G1] In atomic resonance apparatus such as an atomic clock a system of atomic resonators is optically pumped by a beam of radiation modulated by means including means for modulating the sense of rotational polarization of the radiation. The latter means may be a Pockels or Kerr cell adapted to switch the radiation from left to right circular polarization. The polarization modulated beam interacts directly with the resonators to cause spin precession and the pumping radiation has no amplitude modulation to interfere with measurements of the absorption of the radiation to determine resonance. The modulation frequency or the magnetic field may be swept at 100 Hz and the output pulse from a photo-cell receiving the radiation after it has passed through the atomic resonators which occurs at resonance may be displayed on a cathode-ray tube, or used to maintain the resonance condition. The invention may be used to lock an oscillator frequency to an atomic standard for a clock or as a magnetometer by measuring the modulation frequency at resonance by means of a counter. Light modulation.-A Pockels cell in which the electric field is perpendicular to the light beam 3, Fig. 7, comprises a crystal 17 in a torroidal resonant cavity 31 which may be fed with microwave energy by a loop 34. A similar cavity may be used to provide a field parallel to the light beam, Fig. 8 (not shown). The crystal may be potassium dihydrogen or dideuterium phosphate or potassium niobate, potassium tantalate, barium tantalate or potassium lithium niobate.

A free spinning annular cylinder like hollow body (12), having a leading (34) and trailing (36) end which are open at the ends, and having a side wall with an inner and outer surface. The leading end contains a balanced, uniformly and heavily weighted rim (14) for generating gyroscopic forces. When the device is lofted forward with a spinning motion (22) about an axis (24) in substantially the direction of flight, the body is gyroscopically stabilized, in reference to direction, attitude and orientation. The weighted rim (14) also shifts the body's center of gravity (42) toward the center of pressure, near the leading edge, which enables creation of lift.

column13: A method of lifting a fifth wheel hitch onto the bed of a pickup truck having a rail pocket in a rear corner portion of its bed sidewall, comprising the steps of: a) providing a mounting post for a crane having a lower portion adapted to be closely received within the rail pocket and an upper crane reception portion extending above the bed sidewall; b) providing a crane having i) a mast having a lower portion adapted to slidingly and rotatably receive the upper crane reception portion of the mounting post therein, and an upper portion extending above the sidewall of the bed; ii) a boom having a rope carrying end portion, and, iii) a rope having one end portion wound on a winch carried by the mast, and an opposite end portion configured to lift an attachment means; c) positioning the post within the rail pocket; d) mating the crane on the post; e) attaching the hitch to the lift attachment means; f) lifting the hitch above the truck bed; g) rotating the mast on the mounting post to thereby swing and position the elevated crane over the truck bed; and finally, h) lowering the positioned hitch onto the truck bed.

Rotary pad holder with quick-release mechanism
column13: An apparatus for holding a pad to a rotary pad machine. The apparatus includes a base piece and a retainer piece. The base piece includes a plurality of base teeth and is attached to a pad driver disc of the rotary pad machine. The retainer piece includes quick-release tabs having locking ribs. When the retainer piece is inserted into the base piece, the locking ribs lock into the base teeth to hold the retainer piece to the base piece. Flanges on the base piece and the retainer piece hold the pad therebetween. To tighten the rotary pad holder, the retainer piece is pressed closer to the base piece until the locking ribs lock into the appropriate base teeth. To loosen the rotary pad holder or change pads, the quick-release tabs are pressed in towards each other which unlocks the locking ribs from the base teeth and the retainer piece can be removed from the base piece. The rotary pad holder does not over tighten or over loosen because any torque applied to the pad holder is resisted by the retainer wall edges hitting against the connecting walls of the base piece.

In the arrangement shown in Fig. 3, a pattern barrel 15 acts on the tails 4 of jack levers 3 and is carried by a rocking arm 11, which is connected by a link 39 to. a lever 37 carrying a pattern barrel 38 arranged to act on the lower sides of the same jack levers, the two pattern barrels acting alternately. The arrangement may be duplicated, additional pattern barrels 35, 40 and jack levers 34 being provided. Fig. 4 shows a modification, in which pattern barrels 15, 31 act on extensions 4, 30 of jack levers 3. column12: Shaped charge tubing cutter performance test apparatus and method
column13: A shaped charge tubing cutter performance test apparatus and procedure comprises a plurality of test coupons, preferably fabricated from a pipe wall section of the test subject. The coupons are configured with a height greater than the axial length of the shaped charge device and a width greater than the nine wall thickness. These coupons are secured around a circular perimeter with the width plane radiating from the perimeter and the thickness edges in parallel alignment. The circular perimeter diameter corresponds to the shaped charge diameter. A shaped charge cutter is centrally positioned within the coupon encirclement and discharged. Penetration of the cutter plasma into the coupons is measured directly. In variation, the entire assembly is encased, subjected to hydraulic pressure corresponding to a desired well depth and discharged.

column13: In a decanting three-phase centrifuge, the position of the paring disc within a paring pump chamber defined by a rotatable bowl is radially adjustable to provide a cut point between a heavy fluid phase and a light fluid phase of a slurry and thereby separate the two phases. At least one sensor senses a fluid parameter of the separated heavy fluid phase and/or the separated light fluid phase and outputs a fluid parameter signal representative of the sensed fluid parameter. The control unit is programmed to, on the fly; receive the fluid parameter signal; determine from the received fluid parameter signal whether the cut point is to be adjusted; and if the cut point is to be adjusted, automatically drive the actuator to radially adjust the paring disc and thereby reset the cut point on the fly while the centrifuge is operating.

Radar reflector arrangement for military aircraft
column13: The aircraft (1) includes a radar reflector (2) arranged so that the radar signature of the combination of aircraft (1) and reflector is different from that of the aircraft alone. This confuses enemy radar either by removing or folding flat the reflector when on a combat mission so that the aircraft on its own has to the enemy a surprisingly low radar cross-section; or, alternatively by making the radar signature of the combination correspond to that of an aircraft of a potential enemy. The axes of the strings of reflecting elements may each be generally straight and in this case their axes may be arranged substantially parallel to one another or may be arranged at an angle to one another. When the axes of the strings of reflecting element arrays are generally parallel to one another the return echoes from the strings reinforce one another and so reflect a greater quantity of radar signal to provide a strong echo.

column13: 7850. Bell, G. W. May 27. Pneumatic springs; dash-pots.-Relates to pneumatic suspension devices for automobiles and like vehicles of the piston-and-cylinder type, and particularly to the type described in Specification 21,700/13 and which are disposed between the wheel and the axle and within the wheel hub. The main objects of the invention are to provide automatic means to maintain the piston air-tight in the cylinder, and to lubricate the same. Oil is supplied to the lower chamber 3<a>, Figs. 1 and 2, of the cylinder 3, to a depth to insure the complete immersion of the piston packing, by a conduit leading from the counterbored front face 1<e> of the piston 1, to which access may be obtained when the cap 16 is removed from the wheel 8. The piston 1 is provided with two packing-rings 11, 12, Figs. 1, 2, and 8, separated by a groove 11<c> leading to an annular chamber 11<b> formed in the piston or in the metallic rings 11<a>, 12<a> used to secure the packing-rings 11, 12 in position. Any oil which passes the packing-ring 12 is thus trapped in the chamber 11<b>. Air under pressure is automatically supplied to the device from time to time, to replace leakage or to enable the device to carry an increased load, through a conduit 9 communicating through a packing-gland 9<a> in the rear counterbored face of the piston, with a vertical conduit 9<b> leading to the annular chamber 11<b> in the piston; the air then passes through a valve 12<b> in the lower face of the chamber 11<b> and bubbles through the oil in the chamber 3<a>, the oil which has accumulated in the chamber 11<b> simultaneously passing back in to the chamber 3<a>. To permit air to escape when necessary, for example to accommodate a lighter load, a conduit 17<a> leads from the upper chamber 1<a> of the piston, through a packing-gland 17<c>, to a conduit 17. To prevent the oil from entering the enlargements 3<b>, Fig. 2, of the air chambers 1<a> of the piston, a tube 13<a> on the piston, communicating by a passage 1<c> with the upper chamber 1<a>, telescopes within a tube 13<6> on the cylinder 3. The bottom of the tube 13<b> is enlarged to form a ferrule 13, which acts in conjunction with the lower end 1<d> of the piston to form a dash-pot when the piston descends. To conserve the oil in the dash-pot formed between the upper end of the piston and the cylinder 3, the vent holes 10, Fig. 2, communicate with an oil reservoir 10<a>, oil being supplied when necessary through a conduit leading from the front counterbored face 1<e> of the piston to the upper face of the boss 1<f>. In a modification, a single conduit is used to convey air to and from the device. The piston 1, Fig. 7, is provided with h a tube 20 joining the air-inlet conduit 9<b> and the outlet conduit 17<a>, and fitted with a check valve 21. The valve 21, which is normally held closed by a spring 21a, is formed at its upper end with a piston 21<b> fitting air-tight in the tube 20 and containing a valve 24. In action, when air under pressure is admitted to the conduit 9<c>, the valve 21 is lifted, and air passes through the valve opening 23; when the air outlet valve is opened, the pressure of the air in the device opens the valve 24, and air escapes through the passages 27<c> and conduit 9<c>.

column13: A training wheel assembly for standard bicycles comprises training wheels connected by resilient legs to a dynamic compression fitting. The wheels project generally rearwardly and outwardly apart from the bicycle rear. Adjustable mounting brackets enable wheel height to be varied. The dynamic compression fitting comprises an adjustable flange section mounted to the bicycle frame within the standard trapezoidal void to the rear of the crank sleeve. A pair of yoke segments can be slidably adjusted to accommodate varying dimensions. An intermediate flexing section resiliently coupled beneath the flange section receives ends of the legs and establishes an up and down pivot. A damper section connected beneath the intermediate section comprises a rigid, tubular sleeve that slidably receives a tubular cap. A resilient grommet coaxially confined between the sleeve and the cap is compressed by an elongated through bolt coaxially penetrating the compression fitting. The bolt establishes a radial pivot.

Method for defrosting a refrigeration system
column13: Apparatus and a method for operating a refrigeration system without reverse cycle defrost are disclosed. A heat exchanger is divided into a plurality of zones, one zone being constantly utilized as a subcooler to both defrost said zone and to subcool the refrigerant. The remaining zones of the heat exchanger are utilized as an evaporator as is known in the art. A selector valve which is capable of indexing liquid refrigerant flow between zones and receiving gaseous refrigerant from the remaining zones is also disclosed. Additionally, a header arrangement having both expansion means and a conduit controlled by check valve is utilized to direct refrigerant flow from the subcooled zones to the remaining zones of the heat exchanger which act as an evaporator.

column13: 13,651. Bell, G. W. June 6. Pneumatic springs.-Relates to pneumaticsuspension devices for motor-vehicles of the type in which the resistance is automatically regulated, to meet changes in the load, by means of the relative movement of the parts, such regulation, however, being unaffected by momentary movements due to vibration or road shocks. Fig. 1 illustrates such a device, in which the body of the vehicle is carried by a compressed-air cylinder B, in which works a piston A mounted on the axle C. When the cylinder is depressed owing to increase in the load, the arm 26 attached thereto causes compression in the chamber 1, and air passes through the orifice 13, and operates the valve 9 so as to open the main cylinder to the air - compressor pipe 18 Similarly, on a decrease in the load, the cylinder B is opened to exhaust. The present invention consists in utilizing the friction and inertia of the valve 9 for the purpose of maintaining it open to pressure until the main cylinder has returned to its usual position, and in positively closing this valve by a non-elastic link so that the closure occurs approximately at the time that the supporting-piston A reaches its normal position of suspension. In the form shown in Fig. 1, the closing-link consists of the rod 5 shouldered at 21 to engage with the piston 4, so that, when the piston rises owing to a decrease in the load, the valve 9 is operated directly. The friction of the valve 9 may be enhanced by suitable packing in adjustable glands or in certain cases by friction disks; and liquid may be employed instead of air to retard its operation. Alternative modifications show the application of the invention to rotary valves of the plug or tappet type; and in certain cases the wire-drawing of the air at 13 is dispensed with, the elimination of road shocks being effected by introducing a certain amount of lost motion before the valve 9 is opened to pressure. In a further modification, the elastic medium may consist of a spiral spring. A baffle, Fig. 11, may be provided on the exhaust pipe for the purpose of recovering oil from the compressed air escaping from the main cylinder B. The invention may be applied to the apparatus described in Specification 14,382/06.

1,234,827. Colour television. BELL & HOWELL CO. 10 Oct., 1968 [10 Oct., 1967], No. 48108/68. Heading H4F. Relates to an apparatus for producing electrical signals indicative of a predetermined colour contact of a coloured image comprising a means for producing alternating first and second colour signal components, each of a different spectral range and a further means for obtaining separate colour signal components from said alternating components. The alternating colour components are produced at one output of a colour television camera 50 by means of a filter 20 through which light from the image passes to be converted into electrical signals by means of a camera tube 15, for example a vidicon. In the present embodiment the filter comprises alternating red and substantially clear filter stripes 22, 21 arranged orthogonally to the direction of scanning of tube 15. The resultant alternating red R and luminance Y signal is amplified at 26 and combined to form Y-R at terminal 30 by means of filters 27 and 29 and an envelope detector 28 and Y + R at terminal 33 by means of filter 32. These signals are then combined as shown to produce the separate Y and R signals at terminals 37 and 46 respectively. The blue component signal is produced in the usual manner using a filter 52 and camera tube 15<SP>1</SP> and is combined with the R and Y signals to produce a green component signal at terminal 65. In an alternative embodiment (Fig. 4, not shown) the camera tube 15<SP>1</SP> is also equipped with a filter (70) similar to filter 20 composed, for example, of alternating blue and clear filter strips. The three component colour signals are separated similarly as before. Alternatively, using the camera of Fig. 4, the colour difference signals R-Y and B-Y may be produced (Fig. 5, not shown). In any of the above embodiments the output signals may be recorded on magnetic tape and in the Fig. 4 embodiment the light passing through the two striped filters 20 and (70) may be recorded on separate frames on an intermittently moving monochromatic photographic film (Fig. 6, not shown), playback being effected by projecting the two sets of recorded images on to the two camera tubes 15 and 15<SP>1</SP> (Fig. 7, not shown).

A charge detonation booster main-cavity is located on the juncture of the charge truncation planes. Explosive in the booster main-cavity is detonated by a shielded primer path. Explosive density in the primer path is less than the main-cavity density. A dense, powdered metal SC liner and an abruptly stepped jet window in the tubing cutter housing improve performance. The axial span of the jet window is preferably aligned with the axial span between the liner bases. A testing apparatus and procedure inexpensively verifies downhole performance.

column13: 1,208,472. Light guides. RANK ORGANISATION Ltd. Feb.28, 1969 [Feb.28, 1968], No.9585/68. Heading G2J. A method of forming a light guide comprises winding a light transmitting filament on to a former 13 whilst effecting relative movement between the former and a guide holding the filament, so that the filament is laid repeatedly over the same endless loop which has at least one crossing point, the bundle formed being severed to give the guide. The former 13 is rotated about its axis 14 whilst the guide is moved longitudinally relative to the former so as to form a figure of eight loop which is severed at the crossing point X-X to give a "Y" guide; if the bundle is also severed at Z two "Y" guides result. The winding may be such that severing at the crossover point gives a "multitailed" guide Fig. 4 (not shown), or the filament may be wound in a sinuous manner Fig. 5 (not shown), or as a re-entrant helix, Fig.6, wherein severing at A gives a long straight guide. The junction of the "Y" guide may be strengthened before or after severing by binding; alternatively the crossing point may be extended circumferentially.

column13: 29,159. White, W. B. Dec. 14. Weft forks. - Relates to means for securing wire prongs to the body of a weft fork. In the arrangement shown in Figs. 3 and 4, the prongs pass through holes 6, and are locked in place by a plate 8 having extensions 9, which engage beneath the turned-over end 7. The outer prongs are made from a single piece of wire, and the plate 8 is secured by a rivet or screw. In the arrangement shown in Figs. 7 and 8, the prongs are bent round a pivot or socket piece, so that they lie in grooves 10. The prongs are then passed through holes 6 in the fork blank 11, and the broad part of the blank is bent round the pivot or socket piece, and is secured by a rivet &c. Figs. 11 and 12 show a modification in which the prongs are secured by a socket-piece 16, which is adapted to fill the space 14 and has grooves 18 to receive the ends of the prongs. The prongs may be arranged as shown in Fig. 14, in which case the socket-piece 16 has lugs 19, Fig. 13, provided with holes 20 to receive the double prong. In the arrangement shown in Figs. 15 and 16, the prongs pass through holes near the end of the fork blank, and the fixing-plate has fingers 26 which engage between the bent ends of the prongs. Notches may be formed in the end of the fork blank to receive upwardly-bent portions of the prongs. The fixing-plate, Fig. 16, and the fork blank may be modified so that half of the socket is formed in each of them. In the arrangement shown in Figs. 27 and 29, the prongs pass through holes in the down-turned end 40 of the fork blank, and have bent ends which engage holes 33. The prongs are secured by riveting the parts 28 of a fixing-plate, Fig. 27, arranged similarly to the fixing-plate described in Specification 432/83. The fixing - plate may be arranged to form a socket-piece instead of a pivot-piece; in this case, the down-turned end 40 is omitted, or has notches, instead of holes, to receive the prongs, . and the ends of the prongs which pass through the holes 33 are bent down over the face of the fork blank. In the arrangement shown in Figs. 36 and 37, the parts 37, 38 are turned down at'right-angles to the body of the fork blank. The prongs, the bent ends of which are passed through the holes in the part 38 and up through holes 39, are secured by a fixing-plate, Fig. 37, which may be grooved to receive the prongs.

A pipe severing tool is arranged to align a plurality of high explosive pellets along a unitizing support structure whereby all explosive pellets are inserted within or extracted from a tubular housing as a singular unit. Electrically initiated exploding wire detonators (EBW) are positioned at opposite ends of the tubular housing for simultaneous detonation by a capacitive firing device. The housing assembly includes a detachable bottom nose that permits the tool to be armed and disarmed without disconnecting the detonation circuitry. Because the tool is not sensitive to stray electrical fields, it may be transported, loaded and unloaded with the EBW detonators in place and connected.

column12: Laser absorption spectroscopy employing varying absorption conditions
column13: In laser absorption spectroscopy a fluid sample is irradiated with a beam of coherent optical radiation preferably in the infrared band. A detector such as an acoustic detector or thermal detector is coupled in acoustic or thermal energy exchanging relation, respectively, with the fluid medium to detect the absorption of energy, if any, by the fluid from the beam of coherent radiation. One or more of the physical or chemical parameters of the fluid or substances interacting with the fluid are changed and resultant changes, if any, are detected in the absorption of energy by the fluid to yield information concerning the fluid or substances interacting with the fluid.

column13: Une structure de réflecteur radar est agencée à partir d'un certain nombre d'éléments réflecteurs (2, 3, 4). Lors de l'utilisation, les éléments réflecteurs (2, 3, 4) sont placés en une configuration non planaire. Les éléments réflecteurs ont une forme stratifiée comprenant un noyau rigide (d, figure 4) et une couche mince et souple (a, figure 4). La couche mince et souple se prolonge intégralement au-dessus des éléments réflecteurs contigus et forme ainsi une charnière souple entre les éléments. Selon un modèle, une structure stratifiée double formée par deux stratifiés simples liés sur leurs faces opposées est utilisée. Une plaque séparatrice est aménagée sur l'un des éléments stratifiés et lors de l'utilisation se déplace vers le haut hors du plan de son élément respectif autour d'une charnière formée par la couche mince et souple. La structure de réflecteur de cet exemple peut s'affaisser en accordéon pour l'emballage, par exemple, dans une boîte utilisée sur un canot de sauvetage.

Apparatus for Recording Video Signals on Magnetic Tape.
column13: 1,155,347. Magnetic video tape recording. BELL & HOWELL CO. 22 Aug., 1967 [22 Aug., 1966], No. 38549/67. Heading G5R. [Also in Division H4] To balance out delay distortion in video signal magnetic tape recording and playback apparatus, a composite video signal including a pattern of horizontal and vertical synchronizing pulses defining the commencement of respective horizontal scanning lines and vertical line sequences is recorded on a magnetic tape driven past a rotating transducer head scanned across the tape at an angle to its direction of movement, and the recorded signals are played back by moving the tape in the same direction as during recording past a position at which it is scanned by a rotating transducer head moving along each recorded track in the direction opposite to that of head movement during recording. Preferably the played-back signals are reproduced by applying them to modulate a scanning beam deflected in a series of horizontal lines synchronous with the horizontal synchronizing pulses in the played-back signal, the direction of scanning of each line being opposite to the direction of line scanning during development of the initial video signal. As shown in Fig. 1, magnetic tape 10 is drawn by a capstan 16 (acting also as a guide roller) from a supply reel around a guide roller 14 and around a fixed drum 12 having a slot 20. The tape is scanned through the slot 20 by magnetic heads 22 and 24 rotated by a motor 28. Reversal of rotation of the heads during playback, as required by the invention, is provided for by a switch 34, which governs the direction of rotation of the motor 28. The motor 28 may be a synchronous motor including a split phase starting winding of which the phase is reversed by the switch 34 to reverse the direction of rotation. Control of proper tracking between the heads and successive tracks on the tape is provided by servo means controlling the motor 18 in a conventional manner. However, because the tape is moving in the same direction both on recording and on playback the foward motion of the tape subtracts from the angle of the track when the heads are rotated in one direction and adds to that angle when the heads are rotated in the reverse direction. This difficulty is overcome by providing guide roller 14 with flanges and making it adjustable along its axis so as to adjust slightly the path of the tape as it passes around drum 12. A complete recording, playback and reproducing arrangement is shown in Fig. 2. The output, from a video receiver 36 for receiving a broadcast television signal, or from a camera, consists of a composite video signal including horizontal and vertical synchronizing pulses together with amplitude-modulated video information. The signal is frequency-modulated at 38, amplified at 40, and fed to the heads 22, 24 through switch 42 for recording. At the same time the signal from receiver 36 may be applied through a switch 44 in the record position to a sync. separating circuit 46. The video information signal is amplified by a video amplifier 48 and applied to modulate the beam of a cathode-ray picture tube 51 in conventional manner. The horizontal and vertical synchronizing pulses are applied to horizontal and vertical scan generators 50 coupled by switches 52 and 54 respectively to tube 51 so that when the switches are in the "record" position, as shown, the normal left-to-right horizontal line scan and top-to-bottom vertical scan are produced. Playback.-It is assumed that the speed of motor 28 has been selected so that one complete frame of information is laid down in a single slant track scanned by one of the heads 22, 24. During playback, all the information in a single track is reproduced in reverse time sequence. This time reversal requires reversal of both the horizontal and vertical scans of tube 51, which is accomplished by switching switches 52 and 54 to the playback position, whereupon sawtooth signals of reverse polarity are applied to the deflection systems of the tube 51. (Switches 42 and 44 are in the playback position). Alternatively, where each pass of a scanning magnetic head records the video information making up a group of lines less than a complete frame, (e.g. one quarter), the vertical scan must be reversed during the reproduction of each group of lines, but the successive groups of lines must be positioned vertically in the order in which they normally occur. The waveform of the vertical scan signal has its slope reversed during each quarter interval of the vertical sweep, in this case, but the average slope is the same as in the normal scan. Where relatively narrow tape is used, and the magnetic heads are rotated substaintially transversely to the direction of tape movement, a single track on the tape may correspond to only a single line of video information. In this case, only the horizontal scan is reversed during playback while the vertical scan is normal.

column12: Digital color-design composite for use in laminated glass
column13: This invention is directed to a plastic composite comprising color images printed onto a polyethylene terephthalate (PET) substrate using thermal transfer (TT) printing technology. The PET layer is then bonded to a second PET layer using a thermally activated adhesive, preferably ethylene vinyl acetate copolymer (EVA). The bonded PET layers are then disposed between two layers of plasticized PVB, forming the plastic composite. The plastic composite can then be placed between two sheets of glass forming the final laminated glass product.

A training wheel assembly for standard bicycles comprises training wheels connected by resilient legs to a dynamic compression fitting. The wheels project generally rearwardly and outwardly apart from the bicycle rear. Adjustable mounting brackets enable wheel height to be varied. The dynamic compression fitting comprises an adjustable flange section mounted to the bicycle frame within the standard trapezoidal void to the rear of the crank sleeve. A pair of yoke segments can be slidably adjusted to accommodate varying dimensions. An intermediate flexing section resiliently coupled beneath the flange section receives ends of the legs and establishes an up and down pivot. A damper section connected beneath the intermediate section comprises a rigid, tubular sleeve that slidably receives a tubular cap. A resilient grommet coaxially confined between the sleeve and the cap is compressed by an elongated through bolt coaxially penetrating the compression fitting. The bolt establishes a radial pivot.

In laser spectroscopy, a sample medium to be analyzed, such as a gas, is interposed in a laser beam and the absorbance of energy by the sample from the laser beam is detected. In addition, the laser beam intensity is detected. A tuner is provided for tuning the wavelength of the laser beam over a plurality of discrete wavelengths to derive an absorbance spectrum of the sample under analysis. The dwell time for each of the various wavelengths of the laser beam is controlled so as to obtain equal watt-seconds of beam power at each of a number of wavelengths, whereby the sensitivity of the laser spectroscopy is normalized for the various wavelengths.

column13: 7608. Bell, W. T. April 13. Systems of clocks; illuminated clocks.-The time of day is indicated at certain intervals, or letters and the like for advertising and other purposes may be formed and exhibited by apparatus such as that shown in Fig. 1. In the opaque front A of a suitable casing is formed a series of perforations A<1>, which are adapted to be closed by shutters A', so that, the case being illuminated from within, illuminated letters and figures may be formed on the front by opening certain shutters. In the same way figures to denote the time of day, with or without the addition of the letters P.M. and A.M., may be displayed at intervals. In this case three actuating-cylinders, mounted loosely on a common shaft G to control the formation of the figures denoting the units and tens of the minutes, and the hours respectively, are used, additional cylinders being used for any additional characters, that it may be desired to display. The cylinders carry longitudinal bars H<5>, which, as the cylinders are rotated, engage with the short ends D' of levers D straddled over a longitudinal bar D<1>, the levers being held in place by an upper bar D<2>. The other ends D<3> of the levers D engage with the bent ends D<6> of wires D<5> hinged to the shutters A'. Thus, through the arrangement described, the bars H<5> operate the shutters. There are, however, slits in the levers H<5> which allow some of the levers D to pass without being operated upon, and so some of the shutters will remain closed while those apertures which go to form the figures or letters will be opened. The first or unit cylinder is rotated a step intermittently by a pawl I<1> engaging with a ratchet I on the cylinder, the pawl being carried on a crank lever I<2> pivoted on the shaft G, and connected by a spring-rod P with the core 14 of a solenoid 15, which, when energized, causes the core to slide downwards towards its centre, thus operating the cylinder. The solenoid is energized every minute by a switch, operated by clockwork. One wheel of the clockwork has a pin which lifts a pivoted lever having a widened end which on its fall passes between two spring contacts and completes the circuit. The second and third cylinders are, by means of sliding bolts operated by cams, put into gear with the first cylinder and thus rotated, a step at certain intervals. The shutters may be dispensed with, the separate illuminations being effected by lamps arranged as described in Specification No. 16,220, A.D. 1897, [Abridgment Class Advertising &c.], which are automatically switched on by mechanism such as that used to lift the shutters. In this case the wires D<5> are connected with pivoted switch - levers having contacts at one end dipping into mercury caps. For the ordinary display of letters &c. a single cylinder is sufficient. According to the Provisional Specification, the arrangement of switch described in Specification No. 3177, A.D. 1899, [Abridgment Class Advertising &c.], may be used in connection with the electric lamps.

column12: Sealing material for use on stacked high-performance fuel cells

A charge detonation booster main-cavity is located on the juncture of the charge truncation planes. Explosive in the booster main-cavity is detonated by a shielded primer path. Explosive density in the primer path is less than the main-cavity density. A dense, powdered metal SC liner and an abruptly stepped jet window in the tubing cutter housing improve performance. The axial span of the jet window is preferably aligned with the axial span between the liner bases. A testing apparatus and procedure inexpensively verifies downhole performance.

column12: REFRIGERATION CIRCUIT DEFROST SYSTEM, METHOD AND COMPONENTS
column13: Refrigeration Circuit Defrost System, Method and Components Apparatus and a method for operating a refrigeration system without reverse cycle defrost are disclosed. A heat exchanger is divided into a plurality of zones, one zone being constantly utilized as a subcooler to both defrost said zone and to subcool the refrigerant. The remaining zones of the heat exchanger are utilized as an evaporator as is known in the art. A selector valve which is capable of indexing liquid refrigerant flow between zones and receiving gaseous refrigerant from the remaining zones is also disclosed. Additionally, a header arrangement having both expansion means and a conduit controlled by check valve is utilized to direct refrigerant flow from the subcooled zones to the remaining zones of the heat exchanger which act as an evaporator.

A novel high voltage power supply is disclosed which generates an unregulated output voltage from a dc input voltage. The magnitude of the unregulated output voltage may exceed the magnitude of the applied dc voltage. This output voltage appears across a capacitor which is in series with an inductor and a switch. The dc voltage is applied across the inductor and switch, and the switch is periodically closed by an oscillator. While the switch is closed, the voltage across the capacitor increases from energy supplied by the dc voltage. When the switch is open, the voltage on the capacitor is further increased by energy that was stored in the inductor while the switch was closed. A sensing circuit controls the opening and closing of the switch. The high voltage power supply is especially adaptable for use with a display of the gas discharge or plasma type.

column12: COMPOSITION AND METHODS FOR PHOTODYNAMIC INHIBITING GROWTH OF A MICROBIAL PLANT PATHOGEN
column13: We describe methods and materials for inhibiting the growth of a microbial pathogen of a plant. The method comprises the steps of applying to the plant a combination of a dye-bearing compound which is a reactive oxygen species photosensitizer; and a copper compound, which increases the microbial lethality of the dye-bearing compound towards the microbial pathogen; and exposing the plant to light to activate the combination of the dye-bearing compound and the copper compound and inhibiting growth of a microbial pathogen of a plant. The combination of the dye-bearing compound and the copper compound may result in a synergistic ability to reduce the growth of a plant pathogen.

column13: The present disclosure describes a scrubber system for removing material from, or smoothing the surface of, an object. According to an example embodiment, the scrubber system comprises one or more scrubbing disks, spacer disks, and retaining collars configured for interlocking with other cooperatively configured scrubbing disks and spacer disks. The scrubbing and spacer disks are arrangeable end-to-end along a shaft extending therethrough and between opposed retaining collars to form a scrubber custom-configured for a particular application. The scrubbing disks may include one or more types arranged, with or without any spacer disks, in any desired configuration. When the scrubbing disks and/or spacer disks are positioned adjacent one another end-to-end, lateral and end mating surfaces at the adjacent ends of the respective scrubbing and/or spacer disks abut one another, limiting relative rotation therebetween and substantially forming a single, contiguous outer surface that prevents removed material from becoming lodged therebetween.

A polymer is prepared by polymerizing a polymerizable component from a mixture containing the polymerizable component and a surfactant, the surfactant and the polymerizable component being present in the mixture in a molar ratio of at least 0.2:1, having an average pore size greater than 4 nm and a density greater than 0.1 g/cc. The polymerizable component can comprise a resorcinol/formaldehyde system and the mixture can comprise an aqueous solution or the polymerizable component can comprise a divinylbenzene/styrene system and the mixture can comprise an organic solution. Alternatively, the polymerizable component can comprise vinylidene chloride or a vinylidene chloride/divinylbenzene system. The polymer may be monolithic, have a BET surface area of at least about 50 m ^{ 2 } /g., include a quantity of at least one metal powder, or have an electrical conductivity greater than 10 Scm ^{ 1 } .

column12: PHOTODYNAMIC METHOD OF INHIBITING GROWTH OF A MICROBIAL PLANT PATHOGEN
column13: We describe methods and materials for inhibiting the growth of a microbial pathogen of a plant. The method comprises the steps of applying to the plant a combination of a dye-bearing compound which is a reactive oxygen species photosensitizer; and a copper compound, which increases the microbial lethality of the dye-bearing compound towards the microbial pathogen; and exposing the plant to light to activate the combination of the dye-bearing compound and the copper compound and inhibiting growth of a microbial pathogen of a plant. The combination of the dye-bearing compound and the copper compound may result in a synergistic ability to reduce the growth of a plant pathogen.

column12: SYSTEM FOR INDICATING ORDERS AND RECORDING DELIVERIES.
Refrigeration circuit defrost system, method and components
column13: Apparatus and a method for operating a refrigeration system without reverse cycle defrost are disclosed. A heat exchanger is divided into a plurality of zones, one zone being constantly utilized as a subcooler to both defrost said zone and to subcool the refrigerant. The remaining zones of the heat exchanger are utilized as an evaporator as is known in the art. A selector valve which is capable of indexing liquid refrigerant flow between zones and receiving gaseous refrigerant from the remaining zones is also disclosed. Additionally, a header arrangement having both expansion means and a conduit controlled by check valve is utilized to direct refrigerant flow from the subcooled zones to the remaining zones of the heat exchanger which act as an evaporator.

1,246,542. Acoustic thermometer. J. F. W. BELL. 27 Jan., 1970 [29 Jan., 1969], No. 4934/69. Heading H4D. In an acoustic thermometer comprising an acoustic transmission line along which ultrasonic pulses are conveyed to and from an acoustic resonator disposed in a region whose temperature is to be sensed, electronic means automatically vary the ultrasound carrier frequency to maintain resonance in the resonator as the temperature of the resonator varies. As shown in Fig. 1, magnetostrictive transducer 3 is silver-soldered or welded to a line 5 having at one end an isolator 1 and reflector 2 and at the other end a coupler 6 and acoustic resonator 7. Line 5 may be supported in loose (low acoustic impedance) mounts to avoid spurious echoes. A transmitted burst of oscillations of envelope a (Fig. 2) gives rise to an echo of envelope b which at resonance has a crossover region, the oscillations before the crossover being 180 degrees outof-phase with those after the crossover. A control loop error signal for varying the carrier frequency of the oscillation source to maintain resonance is derived by establishing early and late time gates c, d, each embracing a few oscillation cycles near the crossover; deriving a reference square wave R and its inverse R (Fig. 3), both synchronous with the carrier frequency; squaring-up the echo signal to give a signal S; applying signals S, R and c to an AND gate to give a first output representing the overlap of R and S before crossover; applying signals S, R and d to a second AND gate to give a second output representing the overlap of R and S after crossover; summing the first output and the inverse of the second output; and integrating the summation result. The locked resonance frequency is indicated digitally, and a frequencyto-temperature conversion circuit may feed a digital temperature indicator. Several acoustic resonators used in turn may be connected to the frequency-maintaining and measurement circuitry. Reference waves R and R may be derived by phase-shifting and squaring an output of the carrier frequency source, or, particularly if acoustic transmission lines of different length are used, from an oscillation burst triggered by the onset of the echo signal. Materials for the transmission line and resonator are specified. The thermometer may be used for automatically controlling furnace temperature. Reference has been directed by the Comptroller to Specification 1,146,520.

column12: Methods, media and systems for detecting potato viruses in crop images
column13: A method of detecting potato viruses in a crop image depicting at least one potato plant includes: storing the crop image in a memory; identifying a first region of the crop image depicting potato plant leaves; identifying a plurality of edges within the first region; determining, based on edges within an image segment of the crop image in the first region, whether the image segment satisfies one or more leaf crease criteria indicative of a virus-induced leaf crease symptom; determining whether the image segment satisfies one or more color criteria indicative of a symptom of discoloration caused by a virus; and determining whether the segment shows a symptom of a potato virus based on whether the image segment satisfies one or more of a leaf crease criterion and a color criterion. A system and computer readable medium are also disclosed.

A socket adapter for converting a conventional bottom connected watthour meter housing to a socket-type watthour meter housing. The adapter includes a housing having a watthour meter receiving portion including a plurality of electrical contacts which removably receive the blade terminals of a watthour meter. The contacts are connected via electrical conductors to terminals mounted in an integral terminal portion of the housing. A cover member is removably mountable over the terminal portion of the housing to provide access to the terminals. The terminal portion and the cover cooperate to form guide surfaces which direct the building conductors into engagement with the terminals within the adapter. A surge protector in the form of a pair of wires embedded within the peripheral surface of the watthour meter receiving portion of the housing are connectable through a connector mounted on the back wall of the housing to earth ground.

The present disclosure describes a scrubber system for removing material from, or smoothing the surface of, an object. According to an example embodiment, the scrubber system comprises one or more scrubbing disks, spacer disks, and retaining collars configured for interlocking with other cooperatively configured scrubbing disks and spacer disks. The scrubbing and spacer disks are arrangeable end-to-end along a shaft extending therethrough and between opposed retaining collars to form a scrubber custom-configured for a particular application. The scrubbing disks may include one or more types arranged, with or without any spacer disks, in any desired configuration. When the scrubbing disks and/or spacer disks are positioned adjacent one another end-to-end, lateral and end mating surfaces at the adjacent ends of the respective scrubbing and/or spacer disks abut one another, limiting relative rotation therebetween and substantially forming a single, contiguous outer surface that prevents removed material from becoming lodged therebetween.

column13: An absorption refrigeration system wherein there is provided fluid transfer apparatus comprising a stationary hermetic housing having a cylindrical nonferromagnetic wall encasing annular rotor means within the housing about which a rotatable scoop pump pan is connected for rotation therewith for circulating absorbent solution through the system. column12: REFRIGERATION CIRCUIT DEFROST SYSTEM, METHOD AND COMPONENTS
column13: Refrigeration Circuit Defrost System, Method and Components Apparatus and a method for operating a refrigeration system without reverse cycle defrost are disclosed. A heat exchanger is divided into a plurality of zones, one zone being constantly utilized as a subcooler to both defrost said zone and to subcool the refrigerant. The remaining zones of the heat exchanger are utilized as an evaporator as is known in the art. A selector valve which is capable of indexing liquid refrigerant flow between zones and receiving gaseous refrigerant from the remaining zones is also disclosed. Additionally, a header arrangement having both expansion means and a conduit controlled by check valve is utilized to direct refrigerant flow from the subcooled zones to the remaining zones of the heat exchanger which act as an evaporator.

A socket adapter for converting a conventional bottom connected watthour meter housing to a socket-type watthour meter housing. The adapter includes a housing having a watthour meter receiving portion including a plurality of electrical contacts which removably receive the blade terminals of a watthour meter. The contacts are connected via electrical conductors to terminals mounted in an integral terminal portion of the housing. A cover member is removably mountable over the terminal portion of the housing to provide access to the terminals. The terminal portion and the cover cooperate to form guide surfaces which direct the building conductors into engagement with the terminals within the adapter. A surge protector in the form of a pair of wires embedded within the peripheral surface of the watthour meter receiving portion of the housing are connectable through a connector mounted on the back wall of the housing to earth ground.

column12: HEALTHCARE PROVIDER SEARCH BASED ON EXPERIENCE
column13: The embodiments of the present application relate to providing a distributed network-based system that allows users to search for potential healthcare providers that satisfy certain criteria and to dynamically identify healthcare providers that best meet a user's particular needs as defined by each specific search. In embodiments, the system creates experience score for each particular provider who matches the search criteria. The experience score is dynamically determined based on the type of search that is performed (e.g., search by specialty or search by condition or procedure), the query terms used in the search, and other factors including for example, the medical specialty/specialties the provider practices relative to the search performed, evidence the provider treats a condition and/or performs a procedure that matches the consumer's search, patient volume for the searched condition or procedure, total volume of patients, board certification(s) relevant to searched performed, disciplinary action information, malpractice claims history, and degree level attained by the healthcare provider. In other embodiments, the system dynamically ranks healthcare providers within a search results list from best choice to worst choice based on several factors including, for example, the type of search, the query terms used in the search, the quantity of providers who match the query, the locations of the providers who match the query, and the quality and other characteristics of providers who match the search query.

column12: PHOTODYNAMIC METHOD OF INHIBITING GROWTH OF A MICROBIAL PLANT PATHOGEN
column13: We describe methods and materials for inhibiting the growth of a microbial pathogen of a plant. The method comprises the steps of applying to the plant a combination of a dye-bearing compound which is a reactive oxygen species photosensitizer; and a copper compound, which increases the microbial lethality of the dye-bearing compound towards the microbial pathogen; and exposing the plant to light to activate the combination of the dye-bearing compound and the copper compound and inhibiting growth of a microbial pathogen of a plant. The combination of the dye-bearing compound and the copper compound may result in a synergistic ability to reduce the growth of a plant pathogen.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR COMMINUTION OF BIOMINERALIZATIONS USING MICROBUBBLES
column13: A system and method for ultrasound treatment is presented. The system and method alternatingly provide microbubbles in a target region containing a biomineralization, then insonate the microbubbles using an external ultrasound source. The microbubbles cavitate in the target region, destructively affecting the biomineralization and potentially breaking it or reducing its mass over time as a result of the cavitation action. Spatial orientation or alignment of the external ultrasound source may be achieved for best results using acoustic signatures and spectral representations of the same.

column12: HEALTHCARE PROVIDER SEARCH BASED ON EXPERIENCE
column13: The embodiments of the present application relate to providing a distributed network-based system that allows users to search for potential healthcare providers that satisfy certain criteria and to dynamically identify healthcare providers that best meet a user's particular needs as defined by each specific search. In embodiments, the system creates experience score for each particular provider who matches the search criteria. The experience score is dynamically determined based on the type of search that is performed (e.g., search by specialty or search by condition or procedure), the query terms used in the search, and other factors including for example, the medical specialty/specialties the provider practices relative to the search performed, evidence the provider treats a condition and/or performs a procedure that matches the consumer's search, patient volume for the searched condition or procedure, total volume of patients, board certification(s) relevant to searched performed, disciplinary action information, malpractice claims history, and degree level attained by the healthcare provider. In other embodiments, the system dynamically ranks healthcare providers within a search results list from best choice to worst choice based on several factors including, for example, the type of search, the query terms used in the search, the quantity of providers who match the query, the locations of the providers who match the query, and the quality and other characteristics of providers who match the search query.

SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR COMMINUTION OF BIOMINERALIZATIONS USING MICROBUBBLES
column13: A system and method for ultrasound treatment is presented. The system and method alternatingly provide microbubbles in a target region containing a biomineralization, then insonate the microbubbles using an external ultrasound source. The microbubbles cavitate in the target region, destructively affecting the biomineralization and potentially breaking it or reducing its mass over time as a result of the cavitation action. Spatial orientation or alignment of the external ultrasound source may be achieved for best results using acoustic signatures and spectral representations of the same.

Stop-motions, weft.-A needle loom is provided with a weft-tension stop-motion in which weft passes from one or more spools 12, 13, 14, over pivoted hooks 16 supported from a rod 18, through a guide 21, and thence to the needle. The hooks 16 are normally vertical, but when the weft slackens they assume an horizontal position and come in the path of a reciprocating rod 22, which knocks the rod 18 outwards and stops the loom by means of the handle 19. The needle works in an open-sided tube 6, and is steadied by a projection at its rear end in a similar open-sided tube.

A computer controlled defibrillator comprising a set of electrodes which are engageable with a patient and which are connected to a source of electrical energy by a circuit means. The circuit means comprises storage capacitors, energy selector, computer, manual and reset switches, voltage monitor, current monitor, and output meter. The computer responds to certain external inputs, automatic and manual, and controls the output delivered to the patient. The energy selector permits the selection of the energy which is desired to be delivered to the patient. The sequence is started by closing the manual reset switch which zeroes the output meter and activates the power supply (electrical energy) at a voltage which is dependent on the energy selector. The energy derived from the power supply is stored in the storage capacitors. The energy selector, which is manually set to the energy desired, also feeds an input to the computer. When the manual switch is activated, the computer causes the stored energy source to be connected to the patient through the electrodes. The current monitor and voltage monitor feed instantaneous signals to the computer which computes the energy as a continuous integration process. When the computed energy equals the selected energy, the computer causes the energy source to be disconnected from the patient. The total energy delivered to the patient is indicated as a steady reading on the output meter. A modified form of the defibrillator is also disclosed wherein the magnitude of current in the electrical circuit means may be manually or automatically selected to enable the defibrillator to compensate for the patient's body weight.

column13: A method for applying fluid to a cementitious tile (54) is described. The method comprises: supplying a fluid (14) to a chamber (10); bringing cementitious tile (54) into the chamber (10); and withdrawing gas from the chamber (10) so that gas external to the chamber (10) is drawn into the chamber so that gas external to the chamber is drawn into the chamber and the fluid (14) supplied to the chamber rises to impinge on the cementitious tile (54). Such methods are very effective at removing dust from cementitious tiles, and particularly from perforations or indentations in the tiles. Apparatus for carrying out such methods is also described.

column13: 14,382. Bell, |G. W., and Shelmerdine, A. June 23. Spring wheels; hubs. -Relates to means for lubricating the dash-pot anti-vibration devices applied between the wheels and axles and automobiles &c., described in Specification No. 2301, A.D. 1906. An oil reservoir a, Fig. 1, is formed partly around the upper cylinder b in such a position as to be in the rear of the cylinder when travelling. Air and oil holes i,j are formed in the upper part of the cylinder. By the action of the dash-pot, oil is sucked into the cylinder and forced down tubes c in the piston b, and past spring ball valves e; and passes through openings h to the cupleather g, providing both oil packing and lubrication. The oil above the piston b has access to the upper piston rings. The oil that escapes drops into the hollow arms of the cylinder, and, falling through holes into the outer rotating hub l, is carried up centrifugally, and deflected into the reservoir a by a scraper n, preferably passing through a sieve. Fig. 2 shows a modification in which oil is supplied by a pump through a tube o passing through the air pipe r, and is forced past a valve e to passages c' leading to the cup-leather g. The oil escapes through the axle slots u, u<1>, and is returned to the pump by a flexible pipe. Diagonal grooves are formed on the sides of the axle slots u, u<1> to lubricate the stub axle. Oil in the outside hub finds its way to the ball races.

column12: Improvements in or connected with Velocipedes.
column13: 7914. Bell, G. W., and Shelmerdine, A. March 27. Pneumatic wheels; spring wheels,. hubs.-Relates to arrangements for neutralizing vibration, and consists in placing pneumatic or other spring devices in the plane of the wheel so as to avoid side strain and consequent friction. The Figures show one form of the invention as applied to the wheel hub of a bicycle. The wheel spindle, which is fixed rigidly between the fork ends, is formed of a central ring c and trunnions a. A cap c<1> screws into the ring c and forms a plunger, which works in conjunction with a cylinder d to form the spring device. An inflated air chamber k strengthened by a spring-wire coil k<1>, is placed between the plunger and the cylinder. The cylinder d is provided with hollow trunnions or projections d', within which slide vertically the ends a of the wheel spindle. Cones f are screwed on to the trunnions d' to form, in conjunction with races e<1> and balls d<2>, the ball bearings for the wheel hub e. The ring c and the cylinder d are provided with vertical guide-grooves, between which are placed balls or rollers to reduce friction. The air chamber k may be inflated by means of a valve v, to which access is obtained through an opening in the hub provided with a cover. The cylinder d is preferably formed of two parts, bolted together, so that the spindle a, c and plunger c' may be placed therein ; and the hub flange e<4> is arranged to screw into the hub to enable the spring device to be readily introduced into the hub. The shape of the hub flanges may be modified, a side aperture giving access to the valve v. In a modification, the wheel spindle is not provided with the central ring, but is secured to a suitably-shaped plunger. Two plungers and cylinders may be used, or the parts may be otherwise modified. The spindle a, c and plunger c<1> being rigidly fixed to the fork or frame b and the cylinder d to the hub c, the air chamber k practically forms a cushioning-device between the frame and the wheel to absorb vibration or shocks.

column13: Apparatus suitable for processing semiconductor slices, the apparatus comprises a tank (1) for receiving a jig carrying semiconductor slices, a first supply line (2) for supplying a processing liquid to the tank (1), a supply valve (3) for controlling liquid supply through the first supply line (2), the supply valve (3) being operable in response to changes in fluid pressure at a control port (4) of the supply valve (3) and a second supply line (5) for supplying fluid to the control port (4) to control operation of the supply valve (3). The second supply line (5) communicates with an inlet (8) of the tank (1) via a control valve (7) which is operable in response to changes within the tank to control the fluid pressure at the control port (4) and so control operation of the supply valve (3). In the arrangement shown in Figure 1, a valve member (7a) of the valve (7) is carried by a platform (9) pivotally mounted within the tank (1). The weight of a jig carrying semiconductor slices acting on the platform (9) causes the platform (9) to tilt to close the control valve (7) thereby increasing the fluid pressure at the control port (4), causing the supply valve to open and so supply liquid to the tank via the inlet (1ʹ).

Loom take-up motions.-Relates to means for producing an automatic recoil in the take-up motion, thereby letting back the warp, when the loom is stopped on the absence or breakage of weft. When this stoppage occurs, a catch G pivoted to an L-shaped bracket E, falls upon and pushes back the catch-rod finger C, thereby giving a partial turn to the catch-rod D, which raises the actuating and retaining devices of the take-up motion, a slip catch and additional ratchet being employed in this connexion. When the loom is started, the thickened part of a projection H bolted to the setting-on handle A raises the catch G, thus liberating the catch-rod finger C so that the actuating and retaining catches may fall into engagement again with the take-up ratchet-wheel. By swivelling back the catch G by the lug J, the catch-rod finger may be liberated, so that the take-up remains in operation with the loom stopped, for use in hand-weaving &c. In a modification, the curved end of a small swivel-piece, resting on the usual fork-slide and pivoted to the setting-on handle, comes behind the catch-rod finger and pushes it back when the loom is stopped. The weaver, if desired, may find the pick in a loose-reed loom by pushing home the fork-slide, lifting the brake, and pushing the spring handle half-way until the pick is found.

column12: Systems and methods for comminution of biomineralization using microbubbles
column13: A system and method for ultrasound therapy are presented. The systems and methods alternately provide microbubbles in a target area containing biomineralization, and then subject the microbubbles to acoustic waves using an external ultrasound source. The microbubbles are cavitated in the target area, destructively affecting the biomineralization, and due to cavitations, may break the biomineralization or reduce the mass of the biomineralization over time. The spatial orientation or alignment of an external ultrasound source may use acoustic features and spectral representations of these acoustic features to achieve optimal results.

column12: Method of removing undesirable fluid from respiration passages by suction catheter assemblies
column13: A method of removing undesirable fluid from the respiration passages of a patient uses a closed system suction catheter assembly having a protective sleeve enclosing an aspirating catheter extending through a sliding seal in a patient coupling. The catheter has an antimicrobial surface such as formed by silver sulfadiazine which reduces the accumulation of bacteria while the catheter is within the protective sleeve and prolongs the useful life of the assembly.

A computer controlled defibrillator comprising a set of electrodes which are engageable with a patient and which are connected to a source of electrical energy by a circuit means. The circuit means comprises storage capacitors, energy selector, computer, manual and reset switches, voltage monitor, current monitor, and output meter. The computer responds to certain external inputs, automatic and manual, and controls the output delivered to the patient. The energy selector permits the selection of the energy which is desired to be delivered to the patient. The sequence is started by closing the manual reset switch which zeroes the output meter and activates the power supply (electrical energy) at a voltage which is dependent on the energy selector. The energy derived from the power supply is stored in the storage capacitors. The energy selector, which is manually set to the energy desired, also feeds an input to the computer. When the manual switch is activated, the computer causes the stored energy source to be connected to the patient through the electrodes. The current monitor and voltage monitor feed instantaneous signals to the computer which computes the energy as a continuous integration process. When the computed energy equals the selected energy, the computer causes the energy source to be disconnected from the patient. The total energy delivered to the patient is indicated as a steady reading on the output meter. A modified form of the defibrillator is also disclosed wherein the magnitude of current in the electrical circuit means may be manually or automatically selected to enable the defibrillator to compensate for the patient's body weight or body resistance.
