Nov. 26 Traction engines, internal-combustion engine. - A plough is provided with a motortractor, the driving- wheels of which are arranged to run at the bottom of the furrows, thus obviating packing the soil of unplouged land. The tractor carries a motor (not shown) driving transmission shaft 3, which is connected through change-speed and reverse gearing with a worm-wheel shaft 18, from which the axles of two driving - wheels situated towards the front and side and the rear and middle of the tractor respectively are driven through chains 24, 23. The axle-boxes of these wheels are adjustable to kecp the chains taut. The plough frame 77 to which are attached the ploughs 78 is connected to the tractor by a draught chain 79 and a lifting- chain 80. The machine is supported in front on the steering-wheels axle-bar 39 by a cable 40, attached at one end to a bracket 41 on the frame and at the other to a winding-drum 43, which passes over a pulley 44 mounted at the top of a column 46 capable of vertical movement within limits in guides 47 in the tractor and secured at its base to the axle-bar 39. The drum 43 is rotated to wind the cable and thus raise the frame on the front axle by clutching its shaft to a chain-wheel 56 constantly driven from the shaft 18. A rack or worm gear may be used for raising the front of the machine. The lifting-chain 80 of the plough frame, after passing over pulleys 81, 82, 83 on the tractor frame, is connected to the base of the column 46, so that the plough frame is raised or lowered with the front part of the tractor frame. The winding-drum-shaft clutch is operated by a hand-lever 86 which is connected with a slotted link 89 adapted to move a bellcrank lever 93, which throws the clutch in or out. A band brake on a brake drum 95 is simultaneously released or tightened, thus permitting the front of the machine to be raised by the winding-drum or to fall slowly by its own weight against the action of the brake. To prevent overwinding, a bell-crank lever, mounted on the guide 47 and having one arm secured to a cable attached to the steering- wheels axle-bar, is moved when the machine has been sufficiently raised, and throws out the clutch and tightens the brake. A pawl falls into a ratchet-wheel on the winding drum to maintain the machine in its raised position. The winding-drum clutch comprises pairs of friction blocks adapted to be expanded to engage an internal flange on a disk secured to the winding-drum shaft by screw-threads on shafts provided with arms angularly moved when the lever 93 is operated. The tractor is steered by front wheels 31, 32 revolving on axles of the Ackerman type, which are capable of swivelling on pins 35, 36, Fig. 6, mounted at the end of the front axle-bar 39. The axles are moved by arms 76 connected by links 75 with a lever 74, which is provided with a boss fitting a square vertical shaft 66, Fig. 1, supported by brackets projecting from the column 46. Levers 65, fitted on the shaft 66 between brackets carried by the guides 47, are operated by chains 64 adapted to be wound on a chain barrel 63 operated from a steering-wheel 58 through worm-wheel gear. The worm-wheel and the lever 65 may be connected by links and levers in place of the chains. A supplementary wheel 84 adjustable in height is fitted on the opposite side of the frame to the driving-wheel 28, to counteract any tendency to overbalance on that side. A brake block operated by a hand-lever acting through toggle-links is arranged to engage the back wheel. The rims of the driving-wheels are fitted with spuds and strakes and may be boxed in to prevent soil from accumulating. The machine may be employed as a tractor by lifting the ploughs clear of the ground and positioning the side driving- wheel on the axle of the end driving-wheel. The machine may be utilized for driving a threshing or other machine by fitting an extra shaft gear and driving-pulley.

column12: Microcode loading with continued program execution
column13: Microcode is loaded into, for example, a processor or I/O module within a computer system without manually halting and restarting the computer system. In other words, microcode can be loaded into the computer system dynamically while data processing continues from the processor or I/O module states just prior to the microcode load with no major interruption to the user. A microcode image is loaded into a processor which is already executing one or more tasks. A request to load microcode into the processor is received. The processor is signalled to suspend task execution. After the microcode image is transferred into the processor, the processor is signalled to resume task execution.

column12: Method for distributed reinforcement learning, program product and storage medium
column13: Methods, systems, and apparatus, including computer programs encoded on a computer storage medium, to select an action to be performed by a reinforcement learning agent interacting with an environment. A current observation characterizing a current state of an environment is received. For each action in a set of a plurality of actions that may be performed by an agent interacting with an environment, a probability distribution over a possible Q-return for an action-current observation pair is determined. For each action, a measure is determined of a concentrated trend relative to possible Q-returns for a probability distribution for an action-current observation pair. Using the metrics of the concentrated trends, an action to be performed by the agent in response to the current observation is selected.

column12: Active Q-switched high power single mode laser
column13: A high power single mode laser is disclosed which includes a Q-switch for switching the laser on in two stages: firstly, to a relatively high loss level just above threshold where it is held to permit a train of relaxation oscillator spikes to be established and then it is switched to a second stage in which the Q-switch is in a lossless state to allow the resonant mode within the laser to build up to maximum power. An optical detector monitors the resonant optical radiation level within the optical resonator and produces an output signal for each of the relaxation spikes. A trigger circuit, responsive to the detected oscillator spikes, triggers the Q-switch so as to switch it to the second or lossless state upon receipt of the second or any other subsequent relaxation oscillator spike, whereby single longitudinal mode operation of the laser is enhanced. A pair of quarter wave plates are disposed on opposite sides of the laser gain medium within the optical resonator to make the power density distribution within the laser gain medium more uniform, thereby further enhancing single longitudinal mode operation. In a preferred embodiment, the trigger circuit includes a divider which is responsive to the detected oscillator spike signals and divides the received spike signals by two or more so that the laser is caused to fire upon initiation of the second or subsequent relaxation oscillator spike.

column12: Downhole process control method utilizing seismic communication
column13: A seismic communication system suitable to communicate information to an underground device is disclosed. A seismic source (preferably on or near the surface of the earth) generates a timed series of seismic shots. These shots are then detected by one or more seismic receivers underground. Depending on the timing of these seismic shots, and the communication protocol selected, various information may be communicated to the underground target. Such a system is particularly desirable when the underground device includes a perforating gun because the perforating gun may not only be remotely detonated without the drawbacks of previous methods, but the detonation of the perforating gun charges may also be detected, giving an indication whether substantially fewer than all of the explosive charges detonated.

column13: A hand-held device 10 for controlling blood flow, or any fluid flow inside a flexible, resilient tubing 100 is designed to flow the blood flow. Device 10 includes a retention unit 20, a restriction unit 30, a control unit 40, and a power unit 50 providing electrical power. Retention unit 20 is illustrated by a clamp backing 106, a chassis and a fixed part of a clamp 120. Restriction unit 30 includes a cam-and- follower unit driven by a motor 103, driving a cam 104 acting on a clamping pin 105. Clamping pin 105 compresses resilient tubing 100 and thus reduces flow, or completely interrupts flow inside resilient tubing 100. The flow control device is supported on the tubing and is powered by a battery because its construction requires only a small amount of the energy for operation of the device.

column12: Framgangsmate for styring av prosess i borehull, bruk av seismisk kommunikasjon.
column13: Seismisk kommunikasjonssystem innrettet til å kommunisere informasjon til en underjordisk enhet (150). En seismisk kilde (110) (fortrinnsvis på eller nære jordoverflata) genererer en timet rekke av seismiske skudd. Disse skuddene blir så detektert av én eller flere underjordiske seismiske mottakere (141). Avhengig av timingen til disse seismiske skuddene og den valgte kommunikasjonsprotokollen, kan forskjellig informasjon bli kommunisert til det underjordiske målet. Et slikt system er spesielt ønskelig når den underjordiske anordningen omfatter en perforeringskanon, fordi perforeringskanonen ikke bare kan detoneres fra avstand uten ulempene ved tidligere fremgangsmåter, men detoneringen av perforeringskanonen kan også detekteres, noe som gir en indikasjon på om vesentlig færre enn alle de eksplosive ladningene ble detonert.

A marinator apparatus for the preparation of pieces of a whole chicken includes a fluid-tight hollow drum with opposing top and bottom walls that are substantially planar and that include an opening with a lid configured to sealingly close the opening. The drum further includes an interior baffle fixed inside that separates the drum into a top compartment accessible only through the top opening and an opposite bottom compartment accessible only through the bottom opening. The drum is supported for rotation by a support axle projecting from one end wall and a drive axle projecting from the opposite end wall. The drive axle includes a driven gear configure to be driven by a powered drive gear.

A fluid heating process which does not utilize an open flame, heat is created by a rotating prime mover(s) driving a hydraulic heat generator. A bone distraction device fixed by screws to a sectioned bone to facilitate multidirectional repositioning of the jaw bone. The expansion device is expandable to cause incremental expansion in the bone for lengthening or widening thereof. Support wires extending from the device can be clipped to desired lengths to accommodate the particular orientation of the device with respect to the bone. Forked or split anchor ends are then attachable to the wire arms and crimped or otherwise secured thereto. The anchor ends engage with respective bone screws so that when the expansion device is activated, the bone is forced apart.

column12: Improvements relating to vehicle air suspension
column13: A bracket (1,2) for a vehicle air suspension comprises a hollow body (13) of aluminium which is adapted to be fixed at its top to a vehicle chassis member, has two opposed side walls (16,17) carrying co-axial bearings (24) at lower ends for a pivot of a trailing arm, and has rigidly retained to and between the side walls a stiffening member (28) of plate form made of aluminium. A lower portion (29) of the stiffening member extends around and below the bearings (24) and an upper portion (30) extends to the top of the body (13) radially of the bearings. The stiffening member strengthens the bracket (1,2) to withstand lateral loading in use. Its preferred form and arrangement concentrates the lateral loading in a plane containing the axis of the bearings (24) and extending through the upper portion (30). A vehicle air suspension including two of the brackets (1,2) has the brackets connected in fixed spaced relationship by a substantially rigid cross member (3), also made of aluminium, which is connected to proximal side walls (16) of the brackets and has part of its cross-section shaped to correspond with, and align with, the lower portions (29) of the stiffening members (28).

column12: High energy severing tool with pressure balanced explosives
column13: A high energy pipe severing tool is arranged to align a plurality of pressure balanced explosive pellets along a unitizing central tube that is selectively separable from a tubular external housing. The explosive pellets are loaded serially in a column and in full view along the entire column as a final charging task. Detonation boosters are pre-positioned and connected to detonation cord for simultaneous detonation at opposite ends of the explosive column. Devoid of high explosive pellets during transport, the assembly may be transported with all boosters and detonation cord connected.

column12: Process and apparatus for smelting iron with mobile fuels
column13: 829,006. Furnaces for smelting iron. ARMCO INTERNATIONAL CORPORATION. June 15, 1956, No. 18690/56. Class 51 (2). [Also in Group II] A method of smelting iron comprises burning a fuel, oxygen and entrained iron ore and fluxing materials in a combustion chamber to give a flame temperature of at least 3000‹ F. and products of combustion reducing to iron, causing the molten iron and slag produced to flow out of the combustion chamber into a hearth containing a body of solid carbonaceous material, and removing the products of combustion while preventing their contact with the carbonaceous material. As shown, a combustion chamber 10 has a burner 12 and a sloping floor 11 leading to a shallow aperture 17 from which molten metal flows into the lower part of a shaft 16 containing a column of coke 20 finally being collected in a hearth 15. A stack 13, situated between the combustion chamber and the shaft, is provided to remove the products of combustion and supply some heat to the coke. A tuyere 25 may be provided to blow oxygen, which may be preheated, into the bottom of the shaft to burn coke if additonal heat is required. In a modification, Fig. 4 (not shown), four combustion chambers may be arranged around a single shaft and, in a further modification, Fig. 5 (not shown), the stack may be on the opposite side of the combustion chamber to the shaft. The products of combustion may be used to reduce iron oxide under fluidized conditions as described in Specification 829,005.

A deformable dispensing tube 1 for containing fluid or viscous substances has an internal device 8, initially located at the sealed end 3 of the tube and adapted to move towards the formed opening 5 at the tube's opposite end when an external force is applied to the tube onto or near the internal device to dispense the contents 16 of the tube through the formed opening. The internal device 8 may be rigid or deformable. Deformable embodiments of the device are preferably resilient. A deformable centre (28, fig 21) of the device may be made from an elastomer material or foamed rubber or may comprise a formed outer skin filled with fluid, gel or gas. A protrusion (12, fig 9) at forward end of the device is adapted to mate with the formed opening 5 to expel as much of the contents of the tube as possible. A flexible seal (15, fig 9) may be provided whereby the sealing pressure between the device and the inner wall of the tube increases as pressure from the contents increases. Non-return features (26, fig 9) which act on the inner walls of the dispensing tube to prevent movement of the device towards the sealed end of the tube are provided at the tail end of the internal device.

column13: A gas ion laser employs two or more independently controlled electrical gas discharges including a longitudinal plasma arc (10) created by a thermionic cathode (1) and an anode (2) and a transverse glow discharge electron beam (11) created within a photocathode reflector (4). These separately controlled gas discharges are arranged in a unique topology that produces highly excited atomic ions on the optical axis of a laser cavity, giving rise to a beam of laser optical radiation characteristic of the gas ion species being excited. The longitudinal plasma arc (10) on the optical axis (40) is heavily populated with ground state thermal ions that are not sufficiently excited to the energetic states required for laser action. The additional energy to excite these ground state thermal ions to the upper laser states is provided by a second more energetic photo-electron and glow discharge electron beam generated by a negatively biased coaxial photocathode reflector (4).

A dual heating process is performed in the absence of an open flame. Heat is created by a rotating prime mover(s) driving a fluid shear heater. The fluid being heated may be glycol or air, depending on the type of heat desired.

column12: Mini-Severing And Back-Off Tool With Pressure Balanced Explosives
column13: A “mini-severing and back-off” tool includes a tubular magazine for a column of explosive pellets that are sized in diameter to provide a predetermined weight of explosive per unit column length. The tubular wall is vented at prescribed intervals for fluid pressure equalization between the internal bore of the tubular and the fluid pressure around the outside of the tubular. A fluid barrier is positioned between one end of the explosive pellet tubular and a detonator or an explosive booster provided to detonate the explosive pellet tubular. The explosive pellet tubular is positioned within the flow bore of a pipe string and adjacent to an intended pipe joint, and the explosive pellet tubular is detonated simultaneously with an application of torque on the pipe string, wherein the torque is applied in the thread release direction to disassemble the intended pipe joint.

column13: Silanes and siloxanes containing a quaternary ammonium group are made by reacting a tertiary amine with a silane or siloxane containing at least one halogen atom separated from Si by at least 3 C atoms. Amines specified are trimethyl-, triethyl-, phenyldimethyl-, phenylethyldimethyl-, chlorophenyldimethyl- and g - chlorobutyldiphenyl - amines, N,N1-ethanopiperazine, N-methylpiperidine, pyridine, pyridazine, pyrazine, pyrimidine and bis-(trimethylsiloxy)methylsilyl - ethyl - a -picoline. The starting silanes may have the formula R1aRbSiX(4- ab), wherein R1 is the g haloalkyl group of at least 3 C atoms, R is H or a monovalent hydrocarbon (saturated or unsaturated) or halohydrocarbon group, X is alkoxy, aroxy, acyloxy or halogen, a is 1, 2, 3 or 4, b is 0, 1, 2 or 3 and a + b = 4. The starting siloxanes are preferably linear siloxanes. The reaction may be effected in a solvent and preferably at 25 DEG to 150 DEG C. In a typical Example (1) g - iodopropyl - pentamethyldisiloxane, obtained by refluxing the corresponding g -chloropropylsiloxane with NaI and anhydrous acetone, was heated with N,N1-ethano-piperazine to yield a white solid which was water-soluble and was of value as a surfactant. Disiloxanes were also used as the starting materials in Examples (2) and (4) to (8), whereas silanes were used in Examples (3) and (13) and linear polysiloxanes in Examples (9), (10) and (11). column12: Process for the production of Polyurethane Foams
column13: 1,162,517. Polyurethane foams. DUNLOP CO. Ltd. 21 Oct., 1966 [12 Nov., 1965], No. 48024/65. Headings C3C and C3R. A cold-curing process for the manufacture of polyurethane foam comprises reacting in a mould without the application of heat a polymeric polyol which is an ethylene oxide tipped polyoxypropylene and a polyisocyanate having 2, 3 or 4 benzene rings each linked by a methylene group and each carrying at least one isocyanate group in the presence of a blowing agent. The polyisocyanate is preferably a diphenylmethane diisocyanate or a polyphenylene polymethylene isocyanate. Suitable polyols are block copolymers of propylene oxide and ethylene oxide or a glycerol-centred oxyethylene tipped polyoxypropylene triol. A catalyst such as a tertiary amine or an organic tin compound or mixtures thereof and a surface-active agent such as a polysiloxaneoxyalkylene block copolymer may also be included in the reaction mixture. Water and/or fluorinated hydrocarbons may be used as blowing agents.
